{
  "title": "Fraud Detection using DevNet Model",
  "authors": ["Shaik Masihullah"],
  "abstract": "This paper proposes a novel approach to leverage a KNN-based similarity measure, along with a variational scaling factor, to provide supervision for the misclassification of unlabeled data. The proposed methodology is focused on leveraging the similarity between the unlabeled and the labeled non-fraud samples, which is fed as supervision while learning on unlabeled data.",
  "keywords": ["fraud detection", "DevNet model", "KNN-based similarity measure", "variational scaling factor"],
  "sections": [
    {
      "title": "Introduction",
      "text": "The paper aims to explore the strategies of enhancing the performance of the DevNet model and maximizing the utility of labeled data."
    },
    {
      "title": "Proposed Methodology",
      "text": "The approach is focused on leveraging the similarity between the unlabeled and the labeled non-fraud samples, which is fed as supervision while learning on unlabeled data. To achieve this, a K Nearest Neighbor algorithm is trained on the available labeled data to learn a decision boundary and classify the unlabeled data into two clusters namely fraud and non-fraud clusters."
    },
    {
      "title": "Experiment",
      "text": "The paper demonstrates the efficacy of the proposed methodology using an internal dataset of user claims for refunds. The results show that the improvised contrastive loss function consistently surpassed the baseline, achieving an average improvement of approximately 5.88% and 6.4% recall respectively."
    },
    {
      "title": "Conclusion & Future Work",
      "text": "The paper concludes by highlighting the potential of the proposed approach in enhancing the performance of the DevNet model and maximizing the utility of labeled data. The future work includes extending the experiment with other similarity scoring techniques like cosine similarity and comparing the performance with the proposed KNN similarity."
    }
  ]
}

