{
  "title": "Store Page Personalization at DoorDash",
  "authors": [
    {
      "name": "Luming Chen",
      "role": "Machine Learning Engineer"
    },
    {
      "name": "Yuan Meng",
      "role": "Machine Learning Engineer"
    },
    {
      "name": "Anthony",
      "role": "Backend Software Engineer"
    }
  ],
  "date": "2023-02-20T00:00:00.000Z",
  "categories": [
    "Personalization",
    "Recommendations",
    "Machine Learning",
    "DoorDash"
  ],
  "tags": [
    "Store Page Personalization",
    "ML Solutions",
    "Vegan Selections",
    "MTML Architectures",
    "Real-Time Features"
  ],
  "content": {
    "text": "At DoorDash, we're committed to providing the best possible experience for our customers. To achieve this, we've developed a robust personalization system that uses machine learning (ML) solutions to recommend relevant and diverse items to consumers from a vast inventory spanning thousands of categories.\n\nOur ML team has been working on Search and Recommendations for retail merchants and products, and we're excited to share some of our latest advancements in this area. In this blog post, we'll delve into the details of our store page personalization system and explore how it's helping us deliver a more personalized experience for our customers.\n\n**Collection Retrieval Model**\n\nThe collection retrieval model is one of the key components of our store page personalization system. It determines which collections are shown to consumers on each page, based on their past engagement with similar collections and items. The model considers features such as popularity, consumer features, past consumer engagement, context features, and item ranking.\n\n**Item Ranking Model**\n\nThe item ranking model determines the horizontal order of items within a collection. We started with a model that predicts CTR because click events contain rich information about consumer preferences and are highly correlated with our business North Stars, including add-to-cart and conversion. However, we found that optimizing for clicks had certain drawbacks, such as up-ranking niche items with high historical CTR that nonetheless only appeal to a small group of shoppers.\n\n**Diversifying Recommendations**\n\nTo diversify our recommendations, we applied maximal marginal relevance to both items and collections after the ranking stage. This approach balances item score and similarity, ensuring that consumers are presented with fresh discoveries and not just similar items or collections.\n\n**Future Personalization Goals**\n\nOur ML team is also incorporating restaurant order histories to inform grocery recommendations to individual consumers. For example, a frequent vegan restaurant patron might appreciate curated vegan selections in our grocery stores. We plan to use consumer behavior sequences as features to better capture users' short-term and long-term interests.\n\n**Conclusion**\n\nAt DoorDash, we're committed to delivering a more personalized experience for our customers through the power of machine learning. Our store page personalization system is just one example of how we're using ML solutions to recommend relevant and diverse items to consumers from a vast inventory spanning thousands of categories.\n\nWe hope this blog post has provided you with a deeper understanding of our approach to store page personalization and the role that ML plays in delivering a more personalized experience for our customers. If you have any questions or would like to learn more about our work, please don't hesitate to reach out.",
    "images": [
      {
        "url": "https://i.imgur.com/9Q6xK8s.png",
        "alt": "Collection Retrieval Model"
      },
      {
        "url": "https://i.imgur.com/3Z4yT7S.png",
        "alt": "Item Ranking Model"
      }
    ]
  }
}

