{
  "title": "Ocelot: A Platform for Observational Causal Inference",
  "authors": ["LinkedIn Data Science Team"],
  "abstract": "This paper presents Ocelot, a platform for observational causal inference. The platform provides a guided form to lead users through the causal study setup, including what output metrics will be measured, what the control/treatment labels are, what confounders should be included, and most importantly the time periods over which each variable (e.g. output metrics, control/treatment labels, and confounders) should be computed.",
  "keywords": ["observational causal inference", "Ocelot platform", "causal study setup", "robustness checks"],
  "sections": [
    {
      "title": "Introduction",
      "text": "Observational causal inference is a crucial tool for data scientists to make informed decisions. However, it can be challenging to set up and execute observational causal studies due to the complexity of the methods involved."
    },
    {
      "title": "The Ocelot Platform",
      "text": "Ocelot is a platform designed to democratize and expedite observational causal inference within data science communities. The platform provides a guided form to lead users through the causal study setup, including what output metrics will be measured, what the control/treatment labels are, what confounders should be included, and most importantly the time periods over which each variable (e.g. output metrics, control/treatment labels, and confounders) should be computed."
    },
    {
      "title": "Methodology",
      "text": "The Ocelot platform offers five methods for observational causal inference: Coarsened Exact Matching (CEM), Doubly Robust (DR) estimator, Instrumental variables (IV) estimation, Fixed effects models (FEM), and Bayesian Structured Time Series (BSTS)."
    },
    {
      "title": "Robustness Checks",
      "text": "The Ocelot platform has automated robustness checks which, if passed, increase confidence in the treatment effect estimates. If the robustness checks fail, that means the methodology cannot be used to estimate the causal effect and the user is not allowed to claim that the estimates are causal."
    },
    {
      "title": "Conclusion",
      "text": "The Ocelot platform has been successful at democratizing and expediting observational causal inference within LinkedIn’s data science community. The platform provides a guided form to lead users through the causal study setup, automated robustness checks, and a central review committee to ensure the reliability of study results."
    }
  ]
}

