{
  "title": "Skill Extraction and Mapping: A Comprehensive Approach",
  "authors": ["Author1", "Author2"],
  "abstract": "This paper presents a comprehensive approach to skill extraction and mapping, which is critical for creating a member-skill graph with heterogeneous edges that enables a deeper understanding of our members and customers on the platform. The proposed architecture and platform address the challenges of extracting skills and mapping them onto the LinkedIn Skills Graph.",
  "keywords": ["skill extraction", "mapping", "LinkedIn Skills Graph", "member-skill graph"],
  "sections": [
    {
      "title": "Introduction",
      "text": "The paper introduces the importance of skill extraction and mapping in creating a member-skill graph with heterogeneous edges that enables a deeper understanding of our members and customers on the platform."
    },
    {
      "title": "Architecture and Platform",
      "text": "The proposed architecture and platform address the challenges of extracting skills and mapping them onto the LinkedIn Skills Graph. The architecture consists of three main components: skill segmentation, skill tagging, and skill expansion."
    },
    {
      "title": "Skill Segmentation",
      "text": "The first component is skill segmentation, which involves parsing the raw input into a well-formed structure. This is done using a job posting or resume as an example."
    },
    {
      "title": "Skill Tagging",
      "text": "The second component is skill tagging, which identifies the mentions of skills in the text. This is done using a trie-based tagger and a semantic approach based on large language model (LLM) text encoders such as Multilingual BERT."
    },
    {
      "title": "Skill Expansion",
      "text": "The third component is skill expansion, which relies on the Skills Graph to query for relevant skills in the same skill group or skills that share structural relationships."
    },
    {
      "title": "Multitask Cross Domain Skill Scoring",
      "text": "The multitask scoring model contains two parts: a shared module and a domain-specific module. The shared module incorporates any available text information for each content piece and skill candidate pair, while the domain-specific module has multiple dedicated model towers from each vertical."
    },
    {
      "title": "Serving Models at Scale",
      "text": "The paper discusses the importance of serving models at scale to ensure LinkedIn runs smoothly. This is done using Knowledge Distillation and hybrid approaches using offline and nearline processors."
    },
    {
      "title": "Product-Driven Model Improvement",
      "text": "The paper presents a feedback loop directly into online Job Posting and member profiles to help with AI model iterations. This includes recruiter skill feedback, seeker skill feedback, and member profile skill feedback."
    }
  ]
}

