{
"article": {
"title": "Budget Constrained Recommendations using Reinforcement Learning",
"authors": ["Author's Name"],
"date": "2023-02-20T00:00:00Z",
"summary": "This article discusses the use of reinforcement learning to improve budget constrained recommendations. The authors propose a Markov Decision Process (MDP) formulation of the problem, where the agent is the recommender system and the environment is the user interacting with the recommender system.",
"keywords": ["reinforcement learning", "budget constrained recommendations", "Markov Decision Process"],
"sections": [
{
"title": "Introduction",
"text": "Budget constrained recommendations are a type of recommendation algorithm that takes into account the limited budget of the user. The goal is to recommend items that maximize the utility while staying within the budget constraint."
},
{
"title": "Problem Formulation",
"text": "The authors propose a Markov Decision Process (MDP) formulation of the problem, where the agent is the recommender system and the environment is the user interacting with the recommender system. The state of the environment/user is characterized by the available time budget and the items examined in the slate at a particular step in the slate browsing process."
},
{
"title": "Reinforcement Learning Algorithm",
"text": "The authors use Temporal Difference learning TD(0) to estimate the value function. The loss function can be minimized using semi-gradient based methods. Once we have a model for q, we can use that as the item scorer in the above slate recommender system architecture."
},
{
"title": "Simulation Results",
"text": "The authors present simulation results showing how the learned recommender policies behave in terms of metric of success, play-rate for different settings of the user budget distributions’s location parameter and the discount factor. The results show that reinforcement learning outperforms contextual bandit in the budget constrained setting."
},
{
"title": "Off-Policy Learning Results",
"text": "The authors also present off-policy learning results using Q-Learning. The loss function for Q-Learning is very similar to the TD(0) loss except that it uses Bellman’s optimality equation instead. The results show that Q-Learning results in similar performance as the on-policy algorithm."
}
],
"references": [
{
"title": "Budget Constrained Recommendations using Reinforcement Learning",
"authors": ["Author's Name"],
