{
  "title": "Analysis of Listing Descriptions for Homes in Majority Non-Hispanic White and Majority Black Neighborhoods",
  "sections": [
    {
      "name": "Introduction",
      "text": "The analysis aims to explore whether the content of listing descriptions can serve as a proxy for protected classes, specifically majority non-Hispanic white and majority Black neighborhoods."
    },
    {
      "name": "Methodology",
      "text": "The study used a dataset of 534,490 listings in majority non-Hispanic white group and 40,031 listings in the majority Black group distributed over 757 distinct counties. The analysis involved computing simple text statistics, key-phrase statistics, and topic modeling."
    },
    {
      "name": "Simple Text Statistics",
      "text": "The study found that listing descriptions from majority non-Hispanic white locations tend to contain significantly more tokens (average of 144.03) compared to those in majority Black locations (average of 102.17)."
    },
    {
      "name": "Key-Phrase Statistics",
      "text": "The analysis revealed distinct and differentiated dominant themes among listing descriptions in majority non-Hispanic white and majority Black neighborhoods. The top phrases for each group were identified, with the most unique phrases focusing on upscale home features, preferred location, superlatives, and illustration photos for majority non-Hispanic white locations, and investment opportunity, current tenant, first-time home buyer opportunity, accepting condition as is, and home renovations for majority Black locations."
    },
    {
      "name": "Topic Modeling Analysis",
      "text": "The study used topic modeling to analyze the content of listing descriptions. The results showed that the dominant themes among listings from majority non-Hispanic white locations were related to upscale home features, preferred location, and superlatives, while those from majority Black locations focused on investment opportunity, current tenant, first-time home buyer opportunity, accepting condition as is, and home renovations."
    },
    {
      "name": "Conclusion",
      "text": "The analysis suggests that the content of listing descriptions can serve as a proxy for protected classes. The study found significant differences in the dominant themes among listing descriptions in majority non-Hispanic white and majority Black neighborhoods, which could be used to inform policies aimed at reducing disparities in housing markets."
    }
  ]
}

{
  "title": "Zectonal's AI Agents and Function Tool Calling",
  "text": "Zectonal's AI agents and function tool calling capabilities have been developed using Rust, a language known for its speed and reliability. The company has observed that enterprises are starting to feel the adverse impact of hallucinations primarily through their Chat and generative text experiences. To address this issue, Zectonal has implemented auditable AI agent communications, which provide visibility into how agents communicate and under what conditions they are called.\n\nThe company's Rust Agentic framework is extensible and supports OpenAI and Anthropic API's. Ollama, an open-source application, is also supported by the framework. Zectonal believes that a hybrid approach to AI agents, combining best-of-breed online and on-premise agents, will be beneficial for maximizing functionality, avoiding lock-in, and minimizing costs.\n\nThe company has also experimented with meta-agents that create more agents, which is analogous to meta-programming but for AI. This concept involves autonomous software agents creating and spawning other software agents. Zectonal's goal is to find an equilibrium where some smaller number of highly specialized and fine-tuned agents exist within an LLM provider, while others can run on-premise via Ollama.",
  "author": "Zectonal",
  "date": "2024"
}
